Keywords and boolean syntax (USPTO or EPO format): seat belt searches these two words, or their plurals and close synonyms. "seat belt" searches this exact phrase, in order. -seat -belt searches for documents not containing either word.

For searches using boolean logic, the default operator is AND with left associativity. Note: this means safety OR seat belt is searched as (safety OR seat) AND belt. Each word automatically includes plurals and close synonyms. Adjacent words that are implicitly ANDed together, such as (safety belt), are treated as a phrase when generating synonyms.

TREATMENT OF TRIPLE-NEGATIVE BREAST CANCER CHARACTERIZED BY Trop-2 EXPRESSION USING SATSITUZUMAB GOVITECAN AND Rad51 INHIBITOR

Abstract
translated from

FIELD: immunology.
SUBSTANCE: present invention relates to immunology, in particular to a method for the treatment of cancer characterized by Trop-2 expression. The method includes the injection to a subject of an antibody-drug conjugate SN-38 (irinotecan) in a combination with Rad51 inhibitor. The specified conjugate is known as IMMU-132 (satsituzumab govitecan). B02 or RI-1 can be used as Rad51 inhibitor. The specified combination of the conjugate and Rad51 inhibitor can reduce the size of solid tumors, reduce or eliminate metastases and is effective for the treatment of cancer diseases resistant to standard treatment methods, such as radiation therapy, chemotherapy or immunotherapy.
EFFECT: present invention allows improving the efficiency of methods for the therapy of a cancer expressing Trop-2.

, TECHNICAL FIELD OF THE INVENTION

[03] -Trop-2 - ( - ADC - antibody-drug conjugate) Rad51 , Trop-2. , -Trop-2 , , , , , (, SN-38) . , , , , SN-38, , , , , . , ( - TNBC - triple-negative breast cancer), ( - SCLC - small cell lung cancer), ( - NSCLC - non-small cell lung cancer), , , , , , , , , Trop-2, . -Trop-2-SN-38, . , CL2A, . , . 1-12, 1-6, 1-5, 6-8 7-8 - . , , , . Trop-2+, . , , , , , I. , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , . Rad51, , B02 ((E)-3--2(2-(-3-))-4(3H)-) (Huang & Mazin, 2014, PLoS ONE 9(6):e100993); RI-1 (3--1-(3,4-)-4-(4-)-1H--2,5-) (Budke et al., 2012, Nucl Acids Res 40:7347-57); DIDS (4,4'--2,2'- ) (Ishida et al., 2009, Nucl Acids Res 37:3367-76); (Takaku et al., 2011, Genes Cells 16:427-36); (Choudhury et al., 2009, Mol Cancer Ther 8:203-13).[03] The present invention relates to combination therapy with anti-Trop-2 antibody-drug conjugates (ADC) and Rad51 inhibitors for the treatment of cancer characterized by Trop-2 expression. Anti-Trop-2 antibody conjugated drugs can be those that induce DNA strand breaks, such as auristatins, calicheamicins, camptothecins (eg SN-38), or anthracyclines. Examples of drugs that induce DNA strand breaks include, but are not limited to, SN-38, topotecan, doxorubicin, etoposide, cisplatin, oxaliplatin, or carboplatin. Preferably, the cancer is triple-negative breast cancer (TNBC), small cell lung cancer (SCLC), non-small cell lung cancer (NSCLC) ), urothelial cancer, stomach cancer, pancreatic cancer, colorectal cancer, prostate cancer, ovarian cancer, kidney cancer, or bladder cancer, although any type of cancer characterized by Trop-2 expression can be treated. More preferably, said CAS is an anti-Trop-2-SN-38 conjugate such as sacituzumab govitecan. In some embodiments, a linker such as CL2A can be used to attach a drug to an antibody or antibody fragment. However, other linkers, other known cytotoxic drugs, and other known methods for conjugating drugs to antibodies can be used. The antibody or fragment thereof can be linked to 1-12, 1-6, 1-5, 6-8, or 7-8 copies of the drug fragment or drug-linker fragment to the antibody or fragment. CAS are used to treat patients who are either resistant to or suffer from relapses with traditional anti-cancer treatments such as chemotherapy. However, in other embodiments, the CAS can be used as a first line treatment for Trop-2 + cancer, such as TNBC. Surprisingly, CAS are used to treat cancer patients who either relapse or do not respond to irinotecan or topetecan therapy, despite the fact that they are also topoisomerase I inhibitors. Combination therapy can be used alone or in conjunction with one or more other therapeutic agents selected from the group consisting of surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, immunomodulators, cytokines, chemotherapeutic agents, proapoptotic agents, antiangiogenic agents, cytotoxic agents, drugs, toxins, radionuclides, RNAi, siRNA, second antibody or antibody fragment, and immunoconjugate. Any Rad51 inhibitor known in the art can be used, such as B02 ((E) -3-benzyl-2 (2- (pyridin-3-yl) vinyl) quinazolin-4 (3H) -one) (Huang & Mazin, 2014, PLoS ONE 9 (6): e100993); RI-1 (3-chloro-1- (3,4-dichlorophenyl) -4- (4-morpholinyl) -1H-pyrrole-2,5-dione) (Budke et al., 2012, Nucl Acids Res 40: 7347 -57); DIDS (4,4'-diisothiocyanostilbene-2,2'-disulfonic acid) (Ishida et al., 2009, Nucl Acids Res 37: 3367-76); galenaquinone (Takaku et al., 2011, Genes Cells 16: 427-36); or imatinib (Choudhury et al., 2009, Mol Cancer Ther 8: 203-13).

LEVEL OF TECHNOLOGY

[04] - (), , , , , HER2- , c , , (de Goeij & Lambert, 2016, Curr Opin Immunol 40:14-231-4; Gravanis et al., 2016, Oncologist 21:102-9; Jerjian et al., 2016, Pharmacotherapy 36:99-116; Govindan et al., 2016, Expert Opin Biol Ther 16:883-93). , , , , . - . , , , .[04] Antibody-drug conjugates (CAS) containing antibodies bound to active therapeutic agents for the selective delivery of a toxic payload to cancer cells are approved for Hodgkin's lymphoma, systemic anaplastic large cell lymphoma, and for HER2-positive metastatic breast cancer. with several new CASs under development that target a variety of antigens associated with hematopoietic and solid tumors (de Goeij & Lambert, 2016, Curr Opin Immunol 40: 14-231-4; Gravanis et al., 2016, Oncologist 21 : 102-9; Jerjian et al., 2016, Pharmacotherapy 36: 99-116; Govindan et al., 2016, Expert Opin Biol Ther 16: 883-93). Almost all UANs use drugs with picomolar toxicity, such as calicheamicin, which breaks down DNA, or auristatin, or maytansine as microtubule inhibitors. They are not used as independent agents due to their high toxicity. However, with appropriate binding to antibodies, their therapeutic window is acceptable, and careful selection of the appropriate antibody and linker technique is critical to successful clinical use.

[05] SN-38, , (CPT-11), I (Garcia-Carbonero & Supko, 2002, Clin Cancer Res 8:641-615; Mathijssen et al., 2001, Clin Cancer Res 7:2182-94). SN-38 , , , ( ), , SN-38, (Cardillo et al., 2011, Clin Cancer Res 17:3157-69; Govindan et al., 2009, Clin Cancer Res 15:6052-61; Moon et al., 2008, J Med Chem 51:6916-267-9). SN-38 ( IMMU-132; ) Trop-2 ( ; -1 EGP-1), , (Cubas et al., 2009, Biochim Biophys Acta 1796:309-14, Trerotola et al., 2013, Oncogene 32:222-33). Trop-2 (Trerotola et al., 2013, Oncogene 32:222-33; Stepan et al., 2011, J Histochem Cytochem 59:701-10), , - Trop-2 , - (Cardillo et al., 2011, Clin Cancer Res 17:3157-69). , Trop-2, , , - , SN-38.[05] The inventors have developed a CAS based on the well-known anticancer drug SN-38, camptothecin, which is an active component of irinotecan (CPT-11), a topoisomerase I inhibitor (Garcia-Carbonero & Supko, 2002, Clin Cancer Res 8: 641- 615; Mathijssen et al., 2001, Clin Cancer Res 7: 2182-94). While SN-38 has a more moderate level of activity compared to drugs used in other CAS, preclinical trials in xenograft tumor models in mice have shown that under optimized conditions (i.e. choice of antibody and linker), CAS obtained with SN-38 were effective and had an extremely favorable therapeutic window (Cardillo et al., 2011, Clin Cancer Res 17: 3157-69; Govindan et al., 2009, Clin Cancer Res 15: 6052-61; Moon et al., 2008, J Med Chem 51: 6916-267-9). One of these SN-38 conjugates (company name IMMU-132; U.S. generic name sacituzumab govitecan) targets Trop-2 (trophoblastic cell surface antigen; also referred to as epithelial glycoprotein-1 or EGP-1), glycoprotein which is highly expressed in many types of epithelial cancer (Cubas et al., 2009, Biochim Biophys Acta 1796: 309-14, Trerotola et al., 2013, Oncogene 32: 222-33). Trop-2 is also present in many corresponding healthy tissues (Trerotola et al., 2013, Oncogene 32: 222-33; Stepan et al., 2011, J Histochem Cytochem 59: 701-10), but studies in cynomolgus macaques expressing crossover -reactive Trop-2 in similar tissues indicate only dose-limiting neutropenia and gastrointestinal toxicity (Cardillo et al., 2011, Clin Cancer Res 17: 3157-69). Since these events are usually associated with irinotecan therapy and since there was no discernible damage to healthy tissues expressing Trop-2, even at relatively high equivalent doses in humans, the inventors assumed that either the antigen is protected in some way in healthy tissues or healthy tissues less affected by the more moderately toxic SN-38.

[06] I (IMMU-132), 2 3- (Starodub et al., 2015, Clin Cancer Res 21:3870-8). 8, 10, 12 18 /, (), , 12 /. , . , , , 2 , 8 10 /.[06] Recently, the authors reported the results of a phase I dose escalation study of sacituzumab govitecan (IMMU-132) given to patients with various types of metastatic epithelial cancer for 2 weeks in 3-week courses of treatment (Starodub et al., 2015, Clin Cancer Res 21: 3870-8). The doses of 8, 10, 12 and 18 mg / kg were tested, and the maximum tolerated dose (MTD), estimated by the tolerability of one course of therapy, was determined as equal to 12 mg / kg. However, at this dose, there were frequent delays during or between courses, and a dose reduction was required. Therefore, for patients to receive multiple courses of therapy with minimal delays or dose reductions, admission was continued at 2 low dose levels, 8 and 10 mg / kg.

[07] IMMU-132 ( ) , IMMU-132 .[07] Despite the promising results with IMMU-132 (sacituzumab govitecan) as monotherapy, there is a need for improved methods and compositions for combination therapy using IMMU-132 and other anticancer therapies.

DISCLOSURE OF THE INVENTION

[08] - (), , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , . Rad51. , , , . , , .[08] In various embodiments, the present invention relates to compositions and methods for treating cancer using antibody-drug conjugates (CAS) used in combination therapies with one or more other therapeutic agents such as surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, immunomodulators, cytokines, chemotherapeutic agents, proapoptotic agents, anti-angiogenic agents, cytotoxic agents, drugs, toxins, radionuclides, RNAi, siRNA, second antibody or antibody fragment, or immunoconjugate. In preferred embodiments, the CAS is used in combination with one or more Rad51 inhibitors. CAS can be used to treat cancers for which standard treatments are ineffective, such as metastatic pancreatic cancer, metastatic colorectal cancer, or triple-negative breast cancer. More preferably, the combination of CAS and another therapeutic agent is more effective than the individual or cumulative effect of an individual treatment.

One of ordinary skill in the art will understand that various factors such as age, general health, specific organ function or weight, and the effect of prior therapy on certain organ systems (e.g. bone marrow) can be taken into account when choosing the optimal dosage of CAS. and that the dosage and / or frequency of administration can be increased or decreased during the course of therapy. The dosage can be repeated as needed, with signs of tumor shrinkage observed after only 4 to 8 doses. The optimized dosages and dosing regimens disclosed herein show unexpected superior efficacy and reduced human toxicity that could not be predicted from animal model studies. Surprisingly, the high efficacy allows the treatment of tumors that have previously been found resistant to one or more conventional anti-cancer treatments. Even more surprisingly, the treatment was effective on tumors that were previously resistant to camptothecins such as irinotecan, the parent compound for SN-38.

[015] -Trop-2 , , , , , , . , . , , . , -Trop-2 , Trop-2.[015] Anti-Trop-2 CAS combination therapy is used to treat cancers such as TNBC, SCLC, NSCLC, urothelial cancer, bladder cancer, stomach cancer, or ovarian cancer. Such use can be first-line, second-line, or in the later stages of cancer development. The compositions and methods of use are effective in camptothecin resistant as well as camptothecin sensitive types of cancer. Typically, anti-Trop-2 CAS is used to treat any cancer that expresses the Trop-2 antigen.

DETAILED DESCRIPTION

Definitions

[052] , .[052] Unless otherwise indicated, the singular forms one or more.

[053] "" 10%. , " 100" 90 110.[053] In the context of this document, the term "approximately" means plus or minus 10%. For example, "about 100" would include any number between 90 and 110.

[054] , , ( ) (, IgG) ( ) , .[054] An antibody, as used herein, refers to a full-length (i.e., naturally occurring or normally recombined immunoglobulin gene fragment) immunoglobulin molecule (e.g., IgG antibody) or immunologically active (i.e., specifically binding) portion of an immunoglobulin molecule, like fragment of an antibody.

[055] , F(ab')2, Fab', Fab, Fv, sFv . IgG4, . , , . " " , , "Fv", , (" scFv").[055] An antibody fragment is an antibody portion such as F (ab ') 2, Fab', Fab, Fv, sFv, and the like. Antibody fragments can also include single domain antibodies and IgG4 semimolecules, as discussed below. Regardless of the structure, the antibody fragment binds to the same antigen that is recognized by the full-length antibody. The term "antibody fragment" also includes isolated fragments consisting of variable regions of antibodies, such as "Fv" fragments, consisting of variable regions of the heavy and light chains and recombinant single-chain polypeptide molecules in which the light and heavy variable regions are linked by a peptide linker ("proteins scFv ").

[056] , , (CDR) , , , . , .[056] A chimeric antibody is a recombinant protein that contains variable domains, including complementarity determining regions (CDRs) of an antibody derived from a single species, preferably a rodent antibody, while the constant domains of an antibody molecule are derived from domains of a human antibody. For veterinary applications, the chimeric antibody constant domains can be obtained from other species, such as a cat or dog.

[057] , CDR ; , (, ). . () .[057] A humanized antibody is a recombinant protein in which the CDR is from an antibody of the same species; for example, a rodent antibody is transferred from the variable heavy and light chains of a rodent antibody into the variable domains of the heavy and light chains of a human (eg, framework sequences). The constant domains of an antibody molecule are derived from domains of a human antibody. In some embodiments, a limited number of framework amino acid residues from a parent (rodent) antibody may be replaced with human antibody framework sequences.

[058] , , , , "" . , , . , , , . Green et al., Nature Genet. 7:13 (1994), Lonberg et al., Nature 368:856 (1994), Taylor et al., Int. Immun. 6:579 (1994). , , . ., , McCafferty et al., Nature 348:552-553 (1990), in vitro . . , , , . , B-. , ., , Johnson and Chiswell, Current Opinion in Structural Biology 3:5564-571 (1993). in vitro B-. . 5567610 5229275, .[058] A human antibody is, for example, an antibody obtained from transgenic mice that have been "engineered" to generate specific human antibodies in response to antigenic challenge. In this method, elements of human heavy and light chain loci are introduced into mouse strains derived from embryonic stem cell lines that contain targeted disruptions of endogenous mouse heavy chain and light chain loci. Transgenic mice can synthesize human antibodies specific for particular antigens, and the mice can be used to produce hybridomas secreting human antibodies. Methods for obtaining human antibodies from transgenic mice are described by Green et al., Nature Genet. 7:13 (1994), Lonberg et al., Nature 368: 856 (1994), and Taylor et al., Int. Immun. 6: 579 (1994). A fully human antibody can also be constructed by genetic or chromosomal transfection techniques, as well as phage display technology, which are all known in the art. See, for example, McCafferty et al., Nature 348: 552-553 (1990), for in vitro production of human antibodies and fragments thereof from immunoglobulin variable domain genes from non-immunized donors. In this method, the antibody variable domain genes are cloned in frame into the gene of the major or minor coat protein of a filamentous bacteriophage and displayed as functional antibody fragments on the surface of the phage particle. Since the filamentous particle contains a copy of the single-stranded DNA of the phage genome, selection based on the functional properties of the antibody also leads to the selection of the gene encoding the antibody exhibiting these properties. Thus, the phage mimics some of the properties of the B cell. Phage display can be performed in various formats, see, for example, Johnson and Chiswell, Current Opinion in Structural Biology 3: 5564-571 (1993). Human antibodies can also be generated by in vitro activated B cells. See US patent No. 5567610 and 5229275, sections of examples of which are incorporated into this application by reference.

[059] , , , , , , . , , , , , , , , , , . .[059] A therapeutic agent is a compound, molecule or atom that is administered separately, simultaneously or sequentially with an antibody fragment, or conjugated to an antibody fragment, that is, an antibody or antibody fragment, or a sub-fragment thereof, and can be used to treat a disease. Examples of therapeutic agents include antibodies, antibody fragments, drugs, toxins, nucleases, hormones, immunomodulators, proapoptotic agents, antiangiogenic agents, boron compounds, photoactive agents or dyes, and radioisotopes. The therapeutic agents used are described in more detail below.

[060] , , / .[060] An immunoconjugate is an antibody, antibody fragment, or fusion protein conjugated to at least one therapeutic and / or diagnostic agent.

[061] , , , , , / . , , .[061] A multispecific antibody is an antibody that can bind simultaneously to at least two targets that have different structures, for example, two different antigens, two different epitopes on the same antigen or hapten and / or antigen or epitope. Multispecific multivalent antibodies are constructs that have more than one binding site, and the binding sites have different specificities.

[062] , . (bsAb) (bsFab) , , , , , , , . .[062] A bispecific antibody is an antibody that can bind simultaneously to two different targets. Bispecific antibodies (bsAb) and bispecific antibody fragments (bsFab) may have at least one arm that specifically binds, for example, to a tumor associated antigen, and at least one other arm that specifically binds to a targeting conjugate that carries therapeutic or diagnostic agent. A variety of bispecific fusion proteins can be produced using molecular engineering.

[064] RS7 IgG1, (Stein et al., Cancer Res. 50:1330, 1990). RS7 46 48 , 13 (Stein et al., Int. J. Cancer Supp. 8:98-102, 1994). EGP-1 ( -1), Trop-2.[064] The RS7 antibody was murine IgG 1 directed against a crude membrane preparation of human primary squamous cell carcinoma of the lung (Stein et al., Cancer Res. 50: 1330, 1990). The RS7 antibody recognizes a 46 to 48 kDa glycoprotein characterized as cluster 13 (Stein et al., Int. J. Cancer Supp. 8: 98-102, 1994). The antigen has been designated EGP-1 (epithelial glycoprotein-1), but is also referred to as Trop-2.

[065] Trop-2 I (Fornaro et al., Int J Cancer 1995; 62:610-8), (Sewedy et al., Int J Cancer 1998; 75:324-30). (Ripani et al., Int J Cancer 1998; 76:671-6), , Trop-2 , Trop-2 (Wang et al., Mol Cancer Ther 2008;7:280-5).[065] Trop-2 is a type I transmembrane protein and has been cloned from both human (Fornaro et al., Int J Cancer 1995; 62: 610-8) and mouse cells (Sewedy et al., Int J Cancer 1998; 75: 324-30). In addition to its role as a tumor-associated calcium signal transducer (Ripani et al., Int J Cancer 1998; 76: 671-6), expression of human Trop-2 has been shown to be required for tumorigenesis and invasiveness of colon cancer cells, which can effectively reduce with polyclonal antibodies against the extracellular domain of Trop-2 (Wang et al., Mol Cancer Ther 2008; 7: 280-5).

[066] Trop-2 (Cubas et al., Biochim Biophys Acta 2009; 1796:309-14) , Trop-2 (Huang et al., Clin Cancer Res 2005; 11:4357-64), (Ohmachi et al., Clin Cancer Res 2006; 12:3057-63; Fang et al., Int J Colorectal Dis 2009; 24:875-84) (Fong et al., Modern Pathol 2008; 21:186-91). , , , Trop-2, in vitro in vivo , (Goldstein et al., Proc Natl Acad Sci USA 2008; 105:20882-7).[066] The growing interest in Trop-2 as a therapeutic target for solid cancers (Cubas et al., Biochim Biophys Acta 2009; 1796: 309-14) is supported by additional studies showing the clinical significance of overexpressed Trop-2 in breast cancer gland (Huang et al., Clin Cancer Res 2005; 11: 4357-64), colorectal cancer (Ohmachi et al., Clin Cancer Res 2006; 12: 3057-63; Fang et al., Int J Colorectal Dis 2009; 24 : 875-84) and oral squamous cell carcinoma (Fong et al., Modern Pathol 2008; 21: 186-91). Particularly noteworthy are recent data indicating that basal prostate cells expressing high levels of Trop-2 are more likely to exhibit in vitro and in vivo stem cell-like activity (Goldstein et al., Proc Natl Acad Sci USA 2008; 105 : 20882-7).

[067] , MAb RS7 (Stein et al., 1990). Trop-2 , , , , , , . MAb RS7 (Stein et al., 1990; Stein et al., 1991).[067] Studies by flow cytometry and immunohistochemical staining have shown that MAb RS7 detects antigen on various types of tumors with limited binding to normal human tissue (Stein et al., 1990). Trop-2 is expressed primarily by carcinomas such as carcinomas of the lung, stomach, bladder, breast, ovary, uterus, and prostate. Localization and therapy studies using radiolabeled murine MAb RS7 in animal models have demonstrated tumor targeting and therapeutic efficacy (Stein et al., 1990; Stein et al., 1991).

[068] RS7 , , , , , (Stein et al., Int. J. Cancer 55:938, 1993). , (Stein et al., Int. J. Cancer 55:938, 1993). , , RS7 .[068] Strong RS7 staining has been demonstrated in tumors of the lung, breast, bladder, ovary, uterus, stomach and prostate (Stein et al., Int. J. Cancer 55: 938, 1993). Lung cancer cases included both squamous cell carcinomas and adenocarcinomas (Stein et al., Int. J. Cancer 55: 938, 1993). Both types of cells are highly stained, indicating that the RS7 antibody does not distinguish between histological classes of non-small cell lung carcinoma.

[069] MAb RS7 - (Stein et al., 1993). RS7 MAb MAb, , , ( ). , (Pastan et al., Cell 47:641, 1986). (Yang et al., Proc. Nat'l Acad. Sci. USA, 85: 1189, 1988). , RS7 .[069] MAb RS7 is rapidly internalized into target cells (Stein et al., 1993). The internalization rate constant for the RS7 MAb is intermediate between the internalization rate constants of the other two rapidly internalizing MAbs that have been shown to be useful for the production of immunotoxins (ibid.). It is well documented that the internalization of immunotoxin conjugates is a requirement for antitumor activity (Pastan et al., Cell 47: 641, 1986). The internalization of drug immunoconjugates has been described as a major factor in antitumor efficacy (Yang et al., Proc. Nat'l Acad. Sci. USA, 85: 1189, 1988). Thus, the RS7 antibody exhibits several important therapeutic properties.

[074] -Trop-2 , . IgG2a (PANOREX) , (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007, Br. J Cancer 96:417-423). , (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). (MT201), -Trop-2, , , ADCC CDC (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). MT110, -Trop-2/-CD3, (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). , , / Trop-2, CD3 Fc-, (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). , , -Trop-2, (Pseudomonas), (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). -Trop-2 - .[074] The use of anti-Trop-2 antibodies has been disclosed for immunotherapeutic agents other than CAS. The mouse IgG2a antibody edrecolomab (PANOREX) has been used to treat colorectal cancer, although the mouse antibody is not well suited for clinical use in humans (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007, Br. J Cancer 96: 417-423). Low dose subcutaneous administration of ecrecolomab has been described to induce humoral immune responses against the vaccine antigen (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). Adecatumumab (MT201), a fully human anti-Trop-2 antibody, has been used in metastatic breast and early prostate cancer and has been reported to act through ADCC and CDC activity (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). MT110, a single chain anti-Trop-2 / anti-CD3 bispecific antibody construct, has been shown to be effective against ovarian cancer (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). Catumaxomab, a mouse / rat hybrid antibody with affinity for binding to Trop-2, CD3 and Fc receptor, has been reported to be active against ovarian cancer (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). Proxinium, an immunotoxin containing an anti-Trop-2 single chain antibody fused to Pseudomonas exotoxin, has been tested in head and neck and bladder cancers (Baeuerle & Gires, 2007). None of these studies disclosed the use of anti-Trop-2 antibody-drug conjugates.

. Camptothecin conjugates.

[075] , , . () (.. , ) , , 1 30 , 1 12 , 6 8 .[075] The following describes non-limiting methods and compositions for preparing immunoconjugates containing the therapeutic agent camptothecin attached to an antibody or antigen-binding fragment of an antibody. In preferred embodiments, the drug solubility is increased by placing a defined polyethylene glycol (PEG) moiety (i.e., PEG containing a certain amount of monomer units) between the drug and the antibody, wherein said PEG is a low molecular weight PEG, preferably containing from 1 up to 30 monomer units, more preferably containing from 1 to 12 monomeric units, most preferably containing from 6 to 8 monomeric units.

[076] , . , , . , . , ( ) N- L- , - , , .[076] Preferably, the first linker binds a drug at one end and may terminate with an acetylene or azide group at the other end. This first linker may contain a defined PEG moiety with an azide or acetylene group at one end and another reactive group such as a carboxylic acid or hydroxyl group at the other end. Said bifunctional defined PEG can be attached to the amino group of the amino alcohol, and the hydroxyl group of the latter can be attached to the hydroxyl group of the drug in carbonate form. Alternatively, a non-azide (or acetylenic) moiety of said defined bifunctional PEG is optionally attached to the N-terminus of an L-amino acid or polypeptide, the C-terminus being attached to the amino group of the amino alcohol, and the hydroxyl group of the latter being attached to the hydroxyl group of the drug in carbonate or carbamate form, respectively.

[077] , - , ( ) , ( ), -( ) - , , . - .[077] A second linker containing an antibody-binding group and a reactive group complementary to the azide (or acetylenic) group of the first linker, namely acetylene (or azide), can interact with the drug- conjugate (first linker) via an acetylene-azide cycloaddition reaction to obtain a final bifunctional drug product that is suitable for conjugation with antibodies directed against diseases. The antibody-binding group is preferably a thiol or thiol-reactive group.

[078] 10- -20 - (), SN-38, . , SN-38, , - -, - . 10- , BOC (-), . .[078] Methods for selectively regenerating a 10-hydroxyl group in the presence of C-20 carbonate in the preparation of a drug-linker precursor using CPT analogs (camptothecin) such as SN-38 are presented below. Other protecting groups for reactive hydroxyl groups in drugs can also be used, such as the phenolic hydroxyl in SN-38, for example, tert-butyldimethylsilyl or tert-butyldiphenylsilyl, and deprotected with tetrabutylammonium fluoride before binding the derivatized drug to the antibody. -binding fragment. The 10-hydroxyl group of the CPT analogs is alternatively protected as an ester or carbonate other than BOC (tert-butyloxycarbonyl) such that the bifunctional CPT is conjugated to the antibody without prior deprotection of this protecting group. After the introduction of the bioconjugate, the protective group is easily deprotected under physiological pH conditions.

[079] - , "-", L2, L3. , L2 , L3 . "-" (+1) (Kolb HC and Sharpless KB, DrugDiscov Today 2003; 8:1128-37), - . - , , . - , , -.[079] In an acetylene-azide combination called "click chemistry", the azide moiety may be on L2 and the acetylene moiety may be on L3. Alternatively, L2 may contain acetylene and L3 may contain azide. "Click chemistry" refers to a copper (+1) catalyzed cycloaddition reaction between an acetylene moiety and an azide moiety (Kolb HC and Sharpless KB, DrugDiscov Today 2003; 8: 1128-37), although alternative forms of click chemistry are known and can be used ... Click chemistry takes place in an aqueous solution at almost neutral pH values and, therefore, lends itself to conjugation with a drug. The advantage of click chemistry is that it is chemoselective and complements other well known chemical conjugation methods such as the thiol-maleimide reaction.

N- , , N- ( ) . 20- 10-- SN-38 L2, - , ( ) , - . , , SN-38 .[082] In an exemplary conjugate of a preferred embodiment of Formula 1, m is 0, A 'is L-valinol, and an exemplary drug is SN-38. In another example of Formula 1, m is 1 and is represented by derivatized L-lysine, A 'is L-valinol, and an example of a drug is SN-38. In this embodiment, an amide bond is first formed between the carboxylic acid of an amino acid, such as lysine, and the amino group of valinol using orthogonal protecting groups for the amino groups of lysine. The protecting group at the N-terminus of lysine is removed while keeping the protecting group intact on the side chain of lysine, and the N-terminus is coupled to the carboxyl group at the specified PEG with an azide (or acetylene) at the other end. The hydroxyl group of valinol is then attached to the 20-chloroformate derivative of 10-hydroxy-protected SN-38, and this intermediate is coupled to the L2 component carrying the antibody-binding moiety as well as the complementary acetylene (or azide) group involved in the click chemistry of cycloaddition. Finally, removal of the protecting groups on both the lysine side chain and SN-38 gives the product in accordance with this example.

The Phe-Lys dipeptide was designed as a cathepsin B cleavage site for the lysosomal enzyme, which is considered important for the intracellular release of the bound drug. Surprisingly, despite the removal of the cathepsin cleavage site, immunoconjugates containing the CL2A linker appear to be more effective in vivo than those containing the CL2 linker.

[089] , - , . MAb (Wong in Chemistry of protein conjugation and cross-linking, CRC Press, Inc., Boca Raton, FL (1991), pp 20-22). , (Willner et al., Bioconjugate Chem. 4:521-527 (1993)) , (), 7 10 ; MAb - . , SN-38 -SN-38 6 8 SN-38 . , , (. 7521541, ).[089] In preferred embodiments, when the bifunctional drug contains a thiol-reactive moiety as the antibody binding group, thiols in the antibody are generated in the lysine groups of the antibody using a thiolating reagent. Methods for introducing thiol groups into antibodies by modifications of MAb lysine groups are well known in the art (Wong in Chemistry of protein conjugation and cross-linking, CRC Press, Inc., Boca Raton, FL (1991), pp 20-22). Alternatively, mild reduction of interchain disulfide bonds on an antibody (Willner et al., Bioconjugate Chem. 4: 521-527 (1993)) using reducing agents such as dithiothreitol (DTT) can form 7 to 10 thiols on the antibody; it has the advantage of including a plurality of drug moieties in the MAb interchain region away from the antigen binding region. In a more preferred embodiment, attachment of SN-38 to reduced disulfide sulfhydryl groups results in an antibody-SN-38 immunoconjugate with 6 to 8 covalently attached SN-38 fragments per antibody molecule. Other methods of providing cysteine residues for attachment of drugs or other therapeutic agents are known, such as the use of cysteine-modified antibodies (see US Pat. No. 7,521,541, the Examples section of which is incorporated herein by reference).

[092] , , -, 10- . , , 10- - () -. , BOC , (). 20-- , , , , . , (MMT) , , , (Walker et al., 2002). , BOC , 3 5 . , 10- , 20 .[092] In the context of the present invention, a method has surprisingly been found by which you can obtain CPT drug linkers, wherein the CPT additionally has a 10-hydroxyl group. This method includes, but is not limited to, protecting the 10-hydroxyl group as a tert-butyloxycarbonyl (BOC) derivative followed by the penultimate drug-linker conjugate intermediate. Typically, removal of the BOC group requires treatment with a strong acid such as trifluoroacetic acid (TFA). Under these conditions, the CPT 20-O-linker carbonate containing the protecting groups to be removed is also susceptible to degradation, resulting in the formation of unmodified CPT. In fact, the rationale for the use of a mildly removable methoxytrityl (MMT) protecting group on the lysine side chain of the linker molecule, as set forth in the art, was precisely to avoid this possibility (Walker et al., 2002). It has been found that selective removal of the phenolic protecting group BOC is possible by carrying out the reactions for short periods of time, optimally 3 to 5 minutes. Under these conditions, the predominant product was one in which the BOC at the 10-hydroxyl position was removed while the carbonate at the 20 position was intact.

[093] 10-- , BOC, 10-. 10-, 10- , in vivo. 10 20 10- He et al. (He et al., Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry 12: 4003-4008 (2004)). 10- SN-38 COR, R , "N(CH3)2-(CH2)n-", n 1 10 , "CH3-(CH2)n-", n 0 10, , "CH3-(CH2)n-O-", n 0 10, "N(CH3)2-(CH2)n-O-", n 2 10, "R1O-(CH2-CH2-O)n-CH2-CH2-O-", R1 , n 0 10. 10- , . 10- , SN-38, . , 20- . 10-- .[093] An alternative approach involves protecting the 10-hydroxy position of the CPT analog with a group other than BOC so that the final product is ready for conjugation with antibodies without the need to remove the 10-OH protecting group. The 10-hydroxy protecting group, which converts 10-OH to a phenolic carbonate or phenolic ester, is easily removed under physiological pH conditions or by esterases after administration of the conjugate in vivo. Faster removal of phenolic carbonate at position 10 compared to tertiary carbonate at position 20 of 10-hydroxycamptothecin under physiological conditions has been described by He et al. (He et al., Bioorganic & Medicinal Chemistry 12: 4003-4008 (2004)). The 10-hydroxy protecting group on SN-38 can be COR, where R can be substituted alkyl such as "N (CH 3 ) 2 - (CH 2 ) n -" where n is 1 to 10 and where the terminal the amino group is optionally in the form of a quaternary salt for increased water solubility or a simple alkyl moiety such as "CH 3 - (CH 2 ) n -" where n is 0 to 10, or may be an alkoxy moiety such as "CH 3 - (CH 2 ) n -O- ", where n is from 0 to 10, or" N (CH 3 ) 2 - (CH 2 ) n -O- ", where n is from 2 to 10, or" R 1 O- (CH 2 -CH 2 -O) n -CH 2 -CH 2 -O- ", where R 1 is ethyl or methyl and n is an integer ranging from 0 to 10. These 10-hydroxy derivatives readily obtained by treatment with chloroformate of the selected reagent if the final derivative is to be a carbonate. Typically, a 10-hydroxy camptothecin such as SN-38 is treated with a molar equivalent of chloroformate in dimethylformamide using triethylamine as base. Under these conditions, the position of 20-OH does not change. The acid chloride of the selected reagent is used to form 10-O-esters.

[097] -, Trop-2, . ., , Kohler and Milstein, Nature 256:495 (1975), Coligan et al. (eds.), CURRENT PROTOCOLS IN IMMUNOLOGY, VOL. 1, pages 2.5.1-2.6.7 (John Wiley & Sons 1991). , , , B-, B- , , , , , , .[097] Methods for producing monoclonal antibodies against virtually any target antigen, such as Trop-2, are well known in the art. See, for example, Kohler and Milstein, Nature 256: 495 (1975), and Coligan et al. (eds.), CURRENT PROTOCOLS IN IMMUNOLOGY, VOL. 1, pages 2.5.1-2.6.7 (John Wiley & Sons 1991). Briefly, monoclonal antibodies can be generated by injecting mice with a composition containing the antigen, removing the spleen to obtain B lymphocytes, fusing B lymphocytes with myeloma cells to produce hybridomas, cloning hybridomas, selecting positive clones that produce antibodies to the antigen, culturing clones, which produce antibodies to the antigen, and the isolation of antibodies from hybridoma cultures.

Such isolation methods include protein-A or protein-G sepharose affinity chromatography, size exclusion chromatography, and ion exchange chromatography. [0100] , , . V ( ) VH ( ) , () (RT-PCR), 5'-RACE . V- MAb , MAb, - . , VL VH (), Orlandi et al. (Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci., USA, 86: 3833 (1989)). V- MAb, Leung et al. (Mol. Immunol., 32:1413 (1995)).[0100] Various methods, such as producing chimeric or humanized antibodies, may include methods for cloning and constructing antibodies. Antigen binding sequences V (variable light chain) and V H (variable heavy chain) for an antibody of interest can be obtained by various molecular cloning techniques such as real-time polymerase chain reaction (PCR) (RT-PCR), 5'-RACE and cDNA library screening. MAb V genes from a cell that expresses murine MAb can be cloned by PCR amplification and sequenced. To confirm their authenticity, the cloned V L and V H genes can be expressed in cell culture as a chimeric antibody (Ab) as described by Orlandi et al. (Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA 86: 3833 (1989)). Based on the V gene sequences, humanized MAbs can be designed and constructed as described by Leung et al. (Mol. Immunol. 32: 1413 (1995)).

.Chimeric antibodies.

[0104] , , , , (CDR) . . , , Orlandietal., Proc. Nat'IAcad. Sci. USA 6:3833 (1989). . , Leung et al., Hybridoma 13:469 (1994) LL2, , V VH LL2, -CD22, IgG1 .[0104] A chimeric antibody is a recombinant protein in which the variable regions of a human antibody are replaced with variable regions, for example, of a murine antibody, including the complementarity determining regions (CDRs) of a murine antibody. Chimeric antibodies exhibit reduced immunogenicity and increased stability when administered to a subject. General methods for cloning murine immunoglobulin variable domains are disclosed, for example, in Orlandietal., Proc. Nat'IAcad. Sci. USA 6: 3833 (1989). Methods for constructing chimeric antibodies are well known to those skilled in the art. As an example, Leung et al., Hybridoma 13: 469 (1994) generated the LL2 chimera by combining the DNA sequences encoding the V and V H domains of mouse LL2, an anti-CD22 monoclonal antibody, with the corresponding human and IgG 1 constant region domains.

.Humanized antibodies.

[0105] MAb (., , Jones et al., Nature 321:522 (1986), Riechmann et al., Nature 332:323 (1988), Verhoeyen et al., Science 239:1534 (1988), Carter et al., Proc. Nat'l Acad. Sci. USA 89: 4285 (1992), Sandhu, Crit. Rev. Biotech. 12: 437 (1992), Singer et al., J. Immun. 150: 2844. (1993)). CDR . (FR) FR . CDR FR , . FR- , . ., , Tempest et al., Biotechnology 9:266 (1991) Verhoeyen et al., Science 239:1534 (1988). FR, 1, 2 3 CDR, CDR , , CDR.[0105] Methods for making humanized MAbs are well known in the art (see, for example, Jones et al., Nature 321: 522 (1986), Riechmann et al., Nature 332: 323 (1988), Verhoeyen et al., Science 239: 1534 (1988), Carter et al., Proc. Nat'l Acad. Sci. USA 89: 4285 (1992), Sandhu, Crit. Rev. Biotech. 12: 437 (1992), and Singer et al., J. Immun 150: 2844 (1993)). A chimeric or murine monoclonal antibody can be humanized by transferring murine CDRs from the heavy and light variable chains of murine immunoglobulin into the corresponding variable domains of a human antibody. The mouse framework regions (FRs) in the chimeric monoclonal antibody are also replaced with human FR sequences. Since simple transfer of mouse CDRs to human FRs often leads to a decrease or even loss of antibody affinity, additional modification may be required to restore the original affinity of the mouse antibody. This can be achieved by replacing one or more human residues in the FR regions with their murine counterparts to obtain an antibody that has good binding affinity for its epitope. See, for example, Tempest et al., Biotechnology 9: 266 (1991) and Verhoeyen et al., Science 239: 1534 (1988). Preferred substitution residues include FR residues that are located within 1, 2, or 3 Angstroms of the side chain of a CDR residue that are adjacent to the CDR sequence or that are suspected to interact with a CDR residue.

Human antibodies

[0106] , , , (, Mancini et al., 2004, New Microbiol. 27:315-28; Conrad and Scheller, 2005, Comb. Chem. High Throughput Screen. 8:117-26; Brekke and Loset, 2003, Curr. Opin. Pharmacol. 3:544-50). , , . ., , McCafferty et al., Nature 348:552-553 (1990). , , , in vivo .[0106] Methods for producing fully human antibodies using either combinatorial approaches or transgenic animals transformed with human immunoglobulin loci are known in the art (e.g., Mancini et al., 2004, New Microbiol. 27: 315-28; Conrad and Scheller, 2005 Comb Chem High Throughput Screen 8: 117-26; Brekke and Loset 2003 Curr Opin Pharmacol 3: 544-50). A fully human antibody can also be constructed by genetic or chromosomal transfection techniques, as well as phage display technology, which are all known in the art. See, for example, McCafferty et al., Nature 348: 552-553 (1990). It is expected that such fully human antibodies will exhibit even fewer side effects than chimeric or humanized antibodies, and will function in vivo as essentially endogenous human antibodies.

[0107] , (, Dantas-Barbosa et al., 2005, Genet. Mol. Res. 4:126-40). , , (Dantas-Barbosa et al., 2005). , , .[0107] In one alternative embodiment, phage display technology can be used to generate human antibodies (eg, Dantas-Barbosa et al., 2005, Genet. Mol. Res. 4: 126-40). Human antibodies can be obtained from healthy people or people who have a certain disease condition such as cancer (Dantas-Barbosa et al., 2005). An advantage of constructing human antibodies from a sick person is that the circulating antibody repertoire can be biased towards antibodies against disease-associated antigens.

[0110] , , , . Green et al., Nature Genet. 7:13 (1994), Lonberg et al, Nature 368: 856 (1994) Taylor etal, Int. Immun. 6: 579 (1994). XENOMOUSE (, Green et al., 1999, J. Immunol. XENOMOUSE , , .[0110] In another alternative embodiment, transgenic animals that have been genetically engineered to produce human antibodies can be used to generate antibodies against essentially any immunogenic target using standard immunization protocols. Methods for obtaining human antibodies from transgenic mice are described by Green et al., Nature Genet. 7:13 (1994), Lonberg et al, Nature 368: 856 (1994) and Taylor et al, Int. In XENOMOUSE and similar animals, the mouse antibody genes were inactivated and replaced with functional human antibody genes, while the rest of the mouse immune system remained intact.

[0111] XENOMOUSE YAC ( ), , IgH Igkappa, , . -, , . XENOMOUSE, , , / , . XENOMOUSE, . , , (Green et al., 1999). , XENOMOUSE, , .[0111] XENOMOUSE was transformed with YAC (Yeast Artificial Chromosomes) configured with germ lines that contained portions of the human IgH and Igkappa loci, including most of the variable region sequences, along with additional genes and regulatory sequences. The human variable region repertoire can be used to generate antibody producing B cells that can be processed into hybridomas by known methods. XENOMOUSE immunized with the target antigen will produce human antibodies using a normal immune response that can be harvested and / or generated using standard methods described above. Various XENOMOUSE strains are available, each capable of producing different classes of antibodies. Transgenically produced human antibodies have been shown to have therapeutic potential while retaining the pharmacokinetic properties of normal human antibodies (Green et al., 1999). One of ordinary skill in the art will understand that the claimed compositions and methods are not limited to the use of the XENOMOUSE system, but any transgenic animal that has been genetically engineered to produce human antibodies can be used.

[0115] . , , . , . 4 - (CTLA4, CD152), 1 (PD1, CD279) 1 (PD-L1, CD274), , -Trop-2, , . -PD1 (MK-3475, MERCK), (BMS-936558, BRISTOL-MYERS SQUIBB), AMP-224 (MERCK) (CT-011, CURETECH LTD.). -PD1 , , ABCAM (AB137132), BIOLEGEND (EH12.2H7, RMP1-14) AFFYMETRIX EBIOSCIENCE (J105, J116, MIH4). -PD-L1 MDX-1105 (MEDAREX), MEDI4736 (MEDIMMUNE), MPDL3280A (GENENTECH) BMS-936559 (BRISTOL-MYERS SQUIBB). -PD-L1 , , AFFYMETRIX EBIOSCIENCE (MIH1). -CTLA4 (Bristol-Myers Squibb) (PFIZER). -PD1 , , ABCAM (AB134090), SINO BIOLOGICAL INC. (11159-H03H, 11159-H08H) THERMO SCIENTIFIC PIERCE (PA5-29572, PA5-23967, PA5-26465, MA1-12205, MA1-35914). (FDA) (Wada et al., 2013, J Transl Med 11:89).[0115] Checkpoint inhibitor antibodies are useful in cancer therapy. Immune checkpoints refer to inhibitory pathways in the immune system that are responsible for maintaining self-sufficiency and modulating the degree of response of the immune system to minimize damage to peripheral tissues. However, tumor cells can also activate immune checkpoints to reduce the effectiveness of the immune response against tumor tissues. Examples of checkpoint inhibitor antibodies against cytotoxic T lymphocyte antigen 4 (CTLA4, also known as CD152), programmed cell death protein 1 (PD1, also known as CD279), and programmed cell death ligand 1 (PD-L1, also known as CD274) can be used in combination with one or more other agents, such as CAS anti-Trop-2, to enhance the effectiveness of the immune response against cells, tissues or disease pathogens. Typical anti-PD1 antibodies include lambrolizumab (MK-3475, MERCK), nivolumab (BMS-936558, BRISTOL-MYERS SQUIBB), AMP-224 (MERCK), and pidilizumab (CT-011, CURETECH LTD.). Anti-PD1 antibodies are commercially available from, for example, ABCAM (AB137132), BIOLEGEND (EH12.2H7, RMP1-14) and AFFYMETRIX EBIOSCIENCE (J105, J116, MIH4). Examples of anti-PD-L1 antibodies include MDX-1105 (MEDAREX), MEDI4736 (MEDIMMUNE), MPDL3280A (GENENTECH), and BMS-936559 (BRISTOL-MYERS SQUIBB). Anti-PD-L1 antibodies are also commercially available, for example from AFFYMETRIX EBIOSCIENCE (MIH1). Examples of anti-CTLA4 antibodies include ipilimumab (Bristol-Myers Squibb) and tremelimumab (PFIZER). Anti-PD1 antibodies are commercially available from, for example, ABCAM (AB134090), SINO BIOLOGICAL INC. (11159-H03H, 11159-H08H) and THERMO SCIENTIFIC PIERCE (PA5-29572, PA5-23967, PA5-26465, MA1-12205, MA1-35914). Ipilimumab recently received approval from the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) for the treatment of metastatic melanoma (Wada et al., 2013, J Transl Med 11:89).

[0116] (MIF - macrophage migration inhibitory factor) . , CD74 MIF (Leng et al., 2003, J Exp Med 197:1467-76). -CD74 MIF- , , , , (, Meyer-Siegler et al., 2004, BMC Cancer 12:34; Shachar & Haran, 2011, Leuk Lymphoma 52:1446-54). (hLL1) -CD74 MIF- .[0116] The macrophage migration inhibitory factor (MIF) is an important regulator of innate and adaptive immunity and apoptosis. CD74 has been reported to be an endogenous receptor for MIF (Leng et al., 2003, J Exp Med 197: 1467-76). The therapeutic effect of anti-CD74 antagonist antibodies on MIF-mediated intracellular pathways may be useful in the treatment of a wide range of disease conditions such as bladder, prostate, breast, lung, and colon cancers (e.g., Meyer-Siegler et al., 2004 , BMC Cancer 12:34; Shachar & Haran, 2011, Leuk Lymphoma 52: 1446-54). Milatuzumab (hLL1) is an example of an anti-CD74 antibody for therapeutic use in the treatment of MIF-mediated diseases.

. Antibody allotypes.

[0119] (Baert et al., 2003, N Engl. J Med 348:602-08). , , (Stickler et al., 2011, Genes and Immunity 12:213-21). . IgG, - , Gm (1976, J. Immunol. 117:1056-59).[0119] The immunogenicity of therapeutic antibodies is associated with an increased risk of infusion reactions and a decrease in the duration of the therapeutic response (Baert et al., 2003, N Engl. J Med 348: 602-08). The extent to which therapeutic antibodies induce an immune response in a host may in part be determined by the allotype of the antibody (Stickler et al., 2011, Genes and Immunity 12: 213-21). An antibody allotype is associated with amino acid sequence variations at specific positions in the antibody constant region sequences. Allotypes of IgG antibodies containing the heavy chain -type constant region are designated as Gm allotypes (1976, J. Immunol. 117: 1056-59).

[0120] IgG1 G1m1 (Stickler et al., 2011, Genes and Immunity 12:213-21). G1m3 (Stickler et al., 2011). , G1m1 , , G1m1 (nG1m1), G1m3 (Stickler et al., 2011). , G1m1, G1m1 (Stickler et al., 2011).[0120] For common human IgG1 antibodies, the most common allotype is G1m1 (Stickler et al., 2011, Genes and Immunity 12: 213-21). However, the G1m3 allotype is also often found in representatives of the Caucasian race (Stickler et al., 2011). G1m1 antibodies have been reported to contain allotype sequences that tend to induce an immune response when administered to non-G1m1 (nG1m1) recipients such as G1m3 patients (Stickler et al., 2011). Antibodies other than the G1m1 allotype are not as immunogenic when given to patients with G1m1 (Stickler et al., 2011).

[0121] G1m1 356 358 CH3 IgG1. nG1m1 356 358 . G1m1, nG1m1 357 , DEL EEM . G1m1 nG1m1 (SEQ ID NO: 7) (SEQ ID NO: 8).[0121] The human allotype G1m1 includes the amino acids aspartic acid at position 356 Kabat and leucine at position 358 Kabat in the CH3 sequence of the IgG1 heavy chain. The nG1m1 allotype contains the amino acids glutamic acid at position 356 according to Kabat and methionine at position 358 according to Kabat. Both the G1m1 and nG1m1 allotypes contain a glutamic acid residue at position 357 according to Kabat, and these allotypes are sometimes referred to as DEL and EEM allotypes. A non-limiting example of heavy chain constant region sequences for antibodies of allotype G1m1 and nG1m1 is shown below for typical antibodies rituximab (SEQ ID NO: 7) and veltuzumab (SEQ ID NO: 8).

[0122] Jefferis Lefranc (2009, mAbs 1:1-7) , IgG, . , G1m3 214 214 G1m17. nG1m1,2 356 , 358 431 . G1m1,2 356 , 358 431 . Jefferis Lefranc (2009) , Km1 153 191 , Km1,2 - 153 191 , Km3 153 191 .[0122] Jefferis and Lefranc (2009, mAbs 1: 1-7) examined sequence variations characteristic of IgG allotypes and their effect on immunogenicity. They reported that the G1m3 allotype is characterized by an arginine residue at Kabat position 214 compared to a lysine residue at Kabat position 214 in the G1m17 allotype. The nG1m1,2 allotype is characterized by glutamic acid at position 356 according to Kabat, methionine at position 358 according to Kabat, and alanine at position 431 according to Kabat. Allotype G1m1,2 is characterized by aspartic acid at position 356 according to Kabat, leucine at position 358 according to Kabat and glycine at position 431 according to Kabat. In addition to heavy chain constant region sequence variants, Jefferis and Lefranc (2009) reported allotype variants in the kappa light chain constant region, with the Km1 allotype characterized by valine at position 153 Kabat and leucine at position 191 Kabat, allotype Km1,2 by alanine at position 153 Kabat and leucine at position 191 Kabat, and the Km3 allotype is characterized by alanine at position 153 Kabat and valine at position 191 Kabat.

EEM DEL, , .[0123] With regard to therapeutic antibodies, veltuzumab and rituximab, respectively, are humanized and chimeric anti-CD20 IgG1 antibodies used to treat a wide variety of hematological malignancies and / or autoimmune diseases. Table 1 shows a comparison of the allotype sequences of rituximab and veltuzumab. As shown in Table 1, rituximab (G1m17.1) is a DEL allotype of IgG1 with an additional sequence change at position 214 on Kabat (CH1 heavy chain) lysine in rituximab compared to arginine in veltuzumab. Veltuzumab has been reported to be less immunogenic in subjects than rituximab (see, for example, Morchhauser et al., 2009, J Clin Oncol 27: 3346-53; Goldenberg et al., 2009, Blood 113: 1062-70; Robak & Robak, 2011, BioDrugs 25: 13-25), an effect that has been attributed to the difference between humanized and chimeric antibodies. However, the difference in allotypes between the EEM and DEL allotypes probably also explains the lower immunogenicity of veltuzumab.

IgG1 G1m3 IgG4 .[0124] To reduce the immunogenicity of therapeutic antibodies in individuals with the nG1m1 genotype, it is desirable to select an antibody allotype corresponding to the G1m3 allotype, characterized by arginine at position 214 according to Kabat, and the nG1m1,2 null allotype. characterized by glutamic acid at position 356 according to Kabat, methionine at position 358 according to Kabat and alanine at position 431 according to Kabat. Nanotels

[0125] 12 15 ( 110 ). -, , . , - , . , pH , (Van Der Linden et al., 1999, Biochim Biophys Act 1431:37-46). , (, , ) (, Hamsen et al., 2007, Appl Microbiol Biotechnol 77:13-22). (VHH) (CH2 CH3). , / . , , IL-6R, vWF, TNF, RSV, RANKL, IL-17A & F IgE (, ABLYNX, , ), (, Saerens et al., 2008, Curr Opin Pharmacol 8:600-8; Muyldermans, 2013, Ann Rev Biochem 82:775-97; Ibanez et al., 2011, J Infect Dis 203: 1063-72).[0125] Nanobodies are single domain antibodies ranging in size from about 12 to 15 kDa (about 110 amino acids in length). Nanobodies can selectively bind to target antigens, such as full-length antibodies, and have a similar affinity for antigens. However, due to their much smaller size, they can better penetrate solid tumors. The smaller size also contributes to the stability of the nanobody, which is more resistant to extreme pH and temperature than full-length antibodies (Van Der Linden et al., 1999, Biochim Biophys Act 1431: 37-46). Single-domain antibodies were originally developed after the discovery that camelids (camels, alpacas, llamas) possess fully functional antibodies without light chains (eg Hamsen et al., 2007, Appl Microbiol Biotechnol 77: 13-22). Heavy chain antibodies are composed of one variable domain (V HH ) and two constant domains (C H 2 and C H 3). Like antibodies, nanobodies can be designed and used as multivalent and / or bispecific constructs. Humanized nanobodies are in commercial development targeting various target antigens such as IL-6R, vWF, TNF, RSV, RANKL, IL-17A & F and IgE (e.g. ABLYNX, Ghent, Belgium), with potential clinical use in cancer and other disorders (e.g., Saerens et al., 2008, Curr Opin Pharmacol 8: 600-8; Muyldermans, 2013, Ann Rev Biochem 82: 775-97; Ibanez et al., 2011, J Infect Dis 203: 1063-72).

[0126] , , . Fc, .[0126] The half-life of nanobodies in plasma is shorter than that of full-length antibodies, and elimination occurs mainly by the renal route. Since nanobodies lack the Fc region, they do not exhibit complement-dependent cytotoxicity.

[0127] , , - , . (, Jones et al., 1986, Nature 321:522, Riechmann et al., 1988, Nature 332:323, Verhoeyen et al., 1988, Science 239:1534, Carter et al., 1992, Proc. Nat'l Acad. Sci. USA 89:4285, Sandhu, 1992, Crit. Rev. Biotech. 12:437, Singer et al., 1993, J. Immun. 150:2844). - FR .[0127] Nanobodies can be obtained by immunizing camels, llamas, alpacas or sharks with a target antigen, followed by mRNA isolation, cloning into libraries and screening for antigen binding. The sequences of nanobodies can be humanized by standard methods (for example, Jones et al., 1986, Nature 321: 522, Riechmann et al., 1988, Nature 332: 323, Verhoeyen et al., 1988, Science 239: 1534, Carter et al. , 1992, Proc. Nat'l Acad. Sci. USA 89: 4285, Sandhu, 1992, Crit. Rev. Biotech. 12: 437, Singer et al., 1993, J. Immun. 150: 2844). Humanization is relatively straightforward due to the high homology between the camel and human FR sequences.

[0129] , F(ab')2, Fab', F(ab)2, Fab, Fv, sFv, scFv . , , . , F(ab')2 . , , Goldenberg, 4036945 4331647 . . Nisonoff et al., Arch Biochem. Biophys. 89:230 (1960); Porter, Biochem. Fragments of antibodies that recognize specific epitopes can be obtained by known methods. For example, F (ab ') 2 fragments can be obtained by pepsin cleavage of an antibody molecule. These and other methods are described, for example, in Goldenberg, US patent No. 4036945 and 4331647 and the references contained therein. See also Nisonoff et al., Arch Biochem. Alternatively, Fab 'expression libraries can be designed (Huse et al., 1989, Science, 246: 1274-1281) to allow rapid and easy identification of monoclonal Fab' fragments with the desired specificity.

[0130] Fv (scFv) VL VH. VL VH , . (L). scFv VL-L-VH, VL N- scFv, VH-L-VL, VH N- scFv. scFv 4704692, 4946778, R. Raag M. Whitlow, "Single Chain Fvs." FASEB Vol. 9:73-80 (1995) R.E. Bird and B.W. Walker Single Chain Antibody Variable Regions, TIBTECH, Vol. 9: 132-137 (1991).[0130] The single-stranded Fv molecule (scFv) contains a VL domain and a VH domain. The VL and VH domains join to form a target binding site. These two domains are additionally covalently linked by a peptide linker (L). The scFv molecule is designated VL-L-VH if the VL domain is the N-terminus of the scFv molecule, or VH-L-VL if the VH domain is the N-terminus of the scFv molecule. Methods for preparing scFv molecules and constructing suitable peptide linkers are described in US Pat. No. 4,704,692, US Pat. No. 4,946,778, R. Raag and M. Whitlow, "Single Chain Fvs." FASEB Vol. 9: 73-80 (1995) and R.E. Bird and B.W. Walker Single Chain Antibody Variable Regions, TIBTECH, Vol. 9: 132-137 (1991).

[0131] , , , . (VHH) , , , (., , Muyldermans et al., TIBS 26:230-235, 2001; Yau et al., J Immunol Methods 281:161-75, 2003; Maass et al., J Immunol Methods 324:13-25, 2007). Single domain antibodies (VHH) can be obtained, for example, from camels, alpacas or llamas by standard immunization methods (see, for example, Muyldermans et al., TIBS 26: 230-235, 2001; Yau et al., J Immunol Methods 281: 161-75, 2003; Maass et al., J Immunol Methods 324: 13-25, 2007). VHHs may have potent antigen-binding properties and may interact with novel epitopes that are not available for conventional VH-VL pairs (Muyldermans et al., 2001). Alpaca serum IgG contains approximately 50% heavy chain-only (HCAb) camelid IgG antibodies (Maass et al., 2007). [0132] E.coli , . . , 100 , F(ab')2. , , , , 50 Fab' . , Fab Fc.[0132] An antibody fragment can also be obtained by proteolytic hydrolysis of a full-length antibody or by expression in E. coli or another host of the DNA encoding the fragment. An antibody fragment can be obtained by pepsin or papain digestion of full length antibodies using conventional methods. For example, an antibody fragment can be obtained by enzymatic cleavage of antibodies with pepsin to obtain an approximately 100 kDa fragment designated F (ab ') 2 . This fragment can be further cleaved using a thiol reducing agent and, optionally, a blocking group for sulfhydryl groups resulting from cleavage of disulfide bonds, to obtain approximately 50 kDa Fab 'monovalent fragment. Alternatively, enzymatic digestion using papain results in two monovalent Fab fragments and an Fc fragment itself.

[0133] , , , , , .[0133] You can also use other methods of cleaving antibodies, such as separation of heavy chains to form monovalent fragments of the light and heavy chains, further cleavage of the fragments, or other enzymatic, chemical or genetic methods, provided that the fragments bind to an antigen that is recognized by an intact antibody.

.Bispecific and multispecific antibodies.

[0134] . , - -. , CD3 -, (Nitta, et al. Lancet. 1990; 355:368-371). -CD3X -Trop-2. -CD3 , B-, -CD3 X -CD19, -CD3 X -CD20, -CD3 X -CD22, -CD3 X -HLA-DR -CD3 X -CD74. , , .[0134] Bispecific antibodies are useful in a number of biomedical applications. For example, a bispecific antibody with binding sites for a tumor cell surface antigen and for a T cell surface receptor can direct the lysis of certain tumor cells by T cells. Bispecific antibodies that recognize gliomas and the CD3 epitope on T cells have been used successfully in the treatment of human brain tumors (Nitta, et al. Lancet. 1990; 355: 368-371). The preferred bispecific antibody is anti-CD3X and anti-Trop-2. In alternative embodiments, an anti-CD3 antibody or fragment thereof may be linked to an antibody or fragment against an antigen associated with a B cell, such as anti-CD3 X anti-CD19, anti-CD3 X anti-CD20, anti-CD3 X anti -CD22, anti-CD3 X anti-HLA-DR, or anti-CD3 X anti-CD74. In certain embodiments, the methods and compositions for conjugation to a therapeutic agent disclosed herein are used with bispecific or multispecific antibodies as targeting fragments.

[0135] , , , 7405320, . , , , (Milstein and Cuello, Nature, 1983; 305:537-540).[0135] Numerous methods for producing bispecific or multispecific antibodies are known, as described, for example, in US Pat. No. 7,405,320, the Examples section of which is incorporated herein by reference. Bispecific antibodies can be produced by the quadroma method, which involves the fusion of two different hybridomas, each of which produces a monoclonal antibody that recognizes different antigenic sites (Milstein and Cuello, Nature, 1983; 305: 537-540).

[0136] (Staerz, et al. Nature, 1985; 314:628-631; Perez, et al. Nature, 1985; 316:354-356). , (Staerz and Bevan. Proc Natl Acad Sci USA. 1986; 83:1453-1457). Fab'- (., , 0453082).[0136] Another method for producing bispecific antibodies uses heterobifunctional cross-linkers to chemically link two different monoclonal antibodies (Staerz, et al. Nature, 1985; 314: 628-631; Perez, et al. Nature, 1985; 316: 354-356 ). Bispecific antibodies can also be generated by reducing each of the two parental monoclonal antibodies to the corresponding semimolecules, which are then mixed and allowed to reoxidize to obtain a hybrid structure (Staerz and Bevan. Proc Natl Acad Sci USA. 1986; 83: 1453-1457). Another alternative involves chemical crosslinking of two or three separately purified Fab 'fragments using appropriate linkers (see, for example, European patent application 0453082).

[0137] , (DeMonte, et al. [0138] VH VL ( 12 ) Fv (scFv) . scFv 4946778 5132405, , . 12 VH VL VH VL , . VH VL, 3 12 , ( ). 0 2 ( ) ( ), , -, , V- (VH--VL VL--VH), .[0138] The related V H and V L domains can be linked by a peptide linker of appropriate composition and length (usually more than 12 amino acid residues) to form a single chain Fv (scFv) with binding activity. Methods for making scFv are disclosed in US Pat. No. 4,946,778 and US Pat. No. 5,132,405, the Examples section, each of which is incorporated herein by reference. Reducing the length of the peptide linker to less than 12 amino acid residues prevents pairing of the V H and V L domains in the same chain and causes the pairing of the V H and V L domains with complementary domains on other chains, which leads to the formation of functional multimers. The polypeptide chains of the V H and V L domains, which are linked to linkers between amino acid residues 3 and 12, form predominantly dimers (so-called diabodies). With linkers between 0 and 2 amino acid residues, trimers (called tri-bodies) and tetramers (called tetrabodies) are preferred, but the precise oligomerization schemes seem to depend on the composition as well as the orientation of the V-domains (V H -linker-V L or V L -linker-V H ), in addition to the length of the linker.

[0139] , , . , (DNL - dock and lock), , (., , 7521056; 7527787; 7534866; 7550143; 7666400; 7858070; 7871622; 7906121; 7906118; 8163291; 7901680; 7981398; 8003111 8034352, , ). , , (AD) (DDD), , , , , . . DNL , . , , .[0139] These methods for producing polyspecific or bispecific antibodies have various difficulties in terms of low yield, purification, low stability, or laboriousness of the method. More recently, a technique known as "dock and lock" (DNL) has been used to produce combinations of virtually any desired antibody, antibody fragment, and other effector molecule (see, for example, US Pat. Nos. 7,521,056; 7,527,787; 7,534,866 ; 7550143; 7666400; 7858070; 7871622; 7906121; 7906118; 8163291; 7901680; 7981398; 8003111 and 8034352, Examples section, each of which is incorporated herein by reference). The method uses complementary protein binding domains called anchor domains (AD) and dimerization and docking domains (DDD), which bind to each other and allow the assembly of complex structures ranging from dimers, trimers, tetramers, quintamers and hexamers. They form stable complexes with high yields without the need for extensive cleaning. The DNL method allows the collection of monospecific, bispecific, or multispecific antibodies. Any of the methods known in the art for producing bispecific or multispecific antibodies can be used in the methods of the present invention.

In some embodiments, a drug or other agent can be linked to an antibody or fragment thereof via a carrier fragment. Carrier moieties can be attached, for example, to reduced SH groups and / or to carbohydrate side chains. The carrier fragment can be attached to the hinge region of the reduced antibody component through the formation of a disulfide bond. Alternatively, such agents can be coupled using a heterobifunctional crosslinker such as N-succinyl 3- (2-pyridyldithio) propionate (SPDP). Yu etal, Int. J. Cancer 56: 244 (1994). (eds.), pages 60-84 (Cambridge University Press 1995). Alternatively, the carrier fragment can be conjugated via a carbohydrate fragment in the Fc region of an antibody.

[0141] . ., , Shih et al., Int. J. Cancer 41:832 (1988); Shih et al., Int. J. Cancer 46:1101 (1990); Shih et al., 5057313, . , , -, . (), .[0141] Methods for conjugating functional groups to antibodies via a carbohydrate fragment of an antibody are well known to those of skill in the art. See, for example, Shih et al., Int. J. Cancer 41: 832 (1988); Shih et al., Int. J. Cancer 46: 1101 (1990); and Shih et al., US Pat. No. 5,057,313, the Examples section of which is incorporated herein by reference. The general method includes contacting an antibody having an oxidized carbohydrate moiety with a carrier polymer that has at least one free amine function. This interaction results in a primary bond of the Schiff base (imine), which can be stabilized by reduction to a secondary amine to form the final conjugate.

[0142] Fc , . . ., , Leung et al., J. Immunol. 154:5919 (1995); 5443953 6254868, . .[0142] The Fc region may be absent if the antibody component of the CAS is an antibody fragment. [0143] - -. - (., , Kolb et al., 2004, Angew Chem Int Ed 40:3004-31; Evans, 2007, Aust J Chem 60:384-95.) -, 1,3- , (Tornoe et al., 2002, J Organic Chem 67:3057-64), "-". , -, ( , ), - , -.[0143] An alternative method for attaching carrier moieties to a targeting molecule involves the use of click chemistry reactions. The click chemistry approach was originally conceived as a way of rapidly forming complex substances by combining small subunits in a modular form (see, for example, Kolb et al., 2004, Angew Chem Int Ed 40: 3004-31; Evans, 2007, Aust J Chem 60 : 384-95.) Various forms of click chemistry are known in the art, such as the 1,3-dipolar copper catalyzed Hugsen reaction (Tornoe et al., 2002, J Organic Chem 67: 3057-64) , which is often called "click-reaction". Other alternatives include cycloaddition reactions such as Diels-Alder reactions, nucleophilic substitution reactions (especially with small strained rings such as epoxy and aziridine compounds), carbonyl chemistry of urea compounds, and reactions involving carbon-carbon double bonds such as alkynes in thioline reactions.

[0144] - , , . , , 1,4- 1,2,3-. , (Rostovstev et al., 2002, Angew Chem Int Ed. 41:2596; Tornoe et al., 2002, J. Org Chem, 67:3057.) , . , - . , - in vitro .[0144] Hugsen's azide-alkyne cycloaddition reaction uses a copper catalyst in the presence of a reducing agent to catalyze the reaction of the terminal alkyne group attached to the first molecule. In the presence of a second molecule containing an azide moiety, the azide reacts with an activated alkyne to form 1,4-disubstituted 1,2,3-triazole. The copper catalyzed reaction proceeds at room temperature and is quite specific that purification of the reaction product is often unnecessary (Rostovstev et al., 2002, Angew Chem Int Ed. 41: 2596; Tornoe et al., 2002, J. Org Chem, 67 : 3057.) Azide and alkyne functional groups are largely inert to biomolecules in aqueous media, which allows the reaction to proceed in complex solutions. The resulting triazole is chemically stable and does not undergo enzymatic degradation, which makes the click chemistry product very stable in biological systems. Although the copper catalyst is toxic to living cells, the copper-based click chemistry reaction can be used in vitro to form an immunoconjugate.

[0145] - (., , Agard et al., 2004, J Am Chem Soc. 126:15046-47). [3+2] - ( ). , 8- , . , . , - ( ). [0145] Click reaction without copper has been proposed for covalent modification of biomolecules (see, for example, Agard et al., 2004, J Am Chem Soc. 126: 15046-47). The copper-free reaction uses a ring voltage instead of a copper catalyst to accelerate the [3 + 2] azide-alkyne cycloaddition reaction (ibid.). For example, cyclooctyne is an 8-carbon ring structure containing an internal alkyne bond. The closed ring structure causes significant deformation of the bond angle in acetylene, which reacts very actively with azide groups to form triazole. Thus, cyclooctine derivatives can be used for click reactions without copper (ibid.).

[0146] - Ning et al.. (2010, Angew Chem Int Ed. 49:3065-68), - , . ( ). , 4- ( ). - , , N- ( ). , - ( ). N-, ( ). - - in vitro.[0146] Another type of copper-free click reaction has been described by Ning et al .. (2010, Angew Chem Int Ed. 49: 3065-68), which involves azide-nitrone cycloaddition promoted by ring voltage. To eliminate the slow rate of the initial cyclooctine reaction, electron-withdrawing groups are attached next to the triple bond (ibid.). Examples of such substituted cyclooctynes include difluorinated cyclooctynes, 4-dibenzocyclooctynol, and azacyclooctyne (ibid.). An alternative reaction without copper involves ring voltage promoted azide-nitrone cycloaddition to give N-alkylated isoxazolines (ibid.). The reaction was reported to have extremely rapid kinetics and was used in a one-pot, three-step protocol for site-specific modification of peptides and proteins (ibid.). Nitrons were obtained by condensation of the corresponding aldehydes with N-methylhydroxylamine, and the cycloaddition reaction took place in a mixture of acetonitrile and water (ibid.). These and other known click chemistry reactions can be used to attach carrier fragments to antibodies in vitro.

[0147] Agard et. al. (2004, J Am Chem Soc. 126:15046-47) , , ( ) N-, N- . - , ( ). Laughlin et al. (2008, Science 320:664-667) , N-. - (DIFO) in vivo.[0147] Agard et. al. (2004, J Am Chem Soc. 126: 15046-47) demonstrated that a recombinant glycoprotein expressed in CHO cells (Chinese hamster ovary cells) in the presence of peracetylated N-azidoacetylmannosamine leads to the bioincorporation of the corresponding N-azidoacetyl sialic acid into glycoprotein carbohydrates. The azido-derivatized glycoprotein specifically reacted with the biotinylated cyclooctin to form the biotinylated glycoprotein, while the control glycoprotein without the azido group remained unlabeled (ibid.). Laughlin et al. (2008, Science 320: 664-667) used a similar method for metabolic labeling of glycans on the cell surface in zebrafish embryos incubated with peracetylated N-azidoacetylgalactosamine. Azido-derivatized glycans have reacted with difluorinated cyclooctin (DIFO) reagents to enable in vivo visualization of glycans.

[0148] - in vivo. Rossin et al. (2010, Angew Chem Int. Ed. 49:3375-78) 52%- in vivo -TAG72 (CC49), - (TCO), 111In- DOTA (1,4,7,10--1,4,7,10- ). TCO- CC49 , , 1 111In- ( ). , SPECT- (SPECT - single-photon emission computed tomography - ) 13:1 ( ). in vivo , TCO .[0148] The Diels-Alder reaction has also been used to label molecules in vivo. Rossin et al. (2010, Angew Chem Int. Ed. 49: 3375-78) reported a 52% in vivo recovery between tumor-localized anti-TAG72 (CC49) antibody carrying the reactive trans-cyclooctene (TCO) moiety and 111 In- labeled tetrazine derivative DOTA (1,4,7,10-tetraazacyclododecane-1,4,7,10-tetraacetic acid). TCO-labeled CC49 antibody was administered to mice carrying colon cancer xenografts, followed by injection 1 day later with a 111 In-labeled tetrazine probe (ibid.). The response of a radiolabeled probe with a tumor localized antibody resulted in a pronounced localization of radioactivity in the tumor, as demonstrated by SPECT imaging (SPECT - single-photon emission computed tomography) of live mice three hours after administration of a radiolabeled probe with a tumor ratio to muscle 13: 1 (ibid.). The results confirmed the in vivo chemical reaction of the molecules labeled with TCO and tetrazine.

[0149] - in vitro in vivo. , . , , , . - , , . , .[0149] Modifications of the click chemistry reactions are suitable for in vitro or in vivo use. The reactive targeting molecule can be formed by either chemical conjugation or biological incorporation. A targeting molecule, such as an antibody or antibody fragment, can be activated with an azide moiety substituted with a cyclooctyne or alkyne group or a nitrone moiety. When the targeting molecule contains an azido or nitrone group, the corresponding targeting construct will contain a substituted cyclooctyne or alkyne group, and vice versa. Such activated molecules can be obtained by metabolic incorporation into living cells, as discussed above.

. Therapeutic treatment.

[0151] , - (), . , , , , , - (, , , , , - , , , , , ), , , -CD22, hLL2 MAb (, . 6183744), CD22 (hRFB4) B- , CD19, CD20, CD21, CD22, CD23, CD37, CD40, CD40L, CD52, CD74, CD80 HLA-DR. , , , , , , , , .. , , , , , , - , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , . , , , , , , , , , , , -, . , , , , .[0151] In another aspect, the invention relates to a method of treating a subject, comprising administering to the subject a therapeutically effective amount of an antibody-drug conjugate (CAS) as described herein. Diseases that can be treated with CAS described herein include, but are not limited to, B cell malignancies (e.g., non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, mantle cell lymphoma, multiple myeloma, Hodgkin's lymphoma, diffuse large B cell lymphoma, Burkitt's lymphoma, follicular lymphoma, acute lymphocytic leukemia, chronic lymphocytic leukemia, hairy cell leukemia), using, for example, an anti-CD22 antibody such as hLL2 MAb (epratuzumab, see US Pat. No. 6,183,744) against another CD22 epitope (hRFB4) or antibodies against other B cell antigens such as CD19, CD20, CD21, CD22, CD23, CD37, CD40, CD40L, CD52, CD74, CD80, or HLA-DR. Other diseases include, but are not limited to, adenocarcinomas of the endodermal epithelium of the digestive system, cancers such as breast cancer and non-small cell lung cancer, and other carcinomas, sarcomas, glial tumors, myeloid leukemias, etc. In particular, antibodies against an antigen, for example, an oncofetal antigen, produced or associated with a malignant solid tumor or neoplasm of the hematopoietic system, for example, the gastrointestinal tract, stomach, colon, esophagus, liver, lung, breast, pancreas, are advantageously used. liver, prostate, ovary, testicle, brain, bone, urothelial or lymphatic tumor, sarcoma or melanoma. Such therapeutic drugs can be administered one or more times, depending on the disease state and tolerance of the conjugate, and can also be used, optionally, in combination with other therapeutic agents such as surgery, external radiation, radioimmunotherapy, immunotherapy, chemotherapy, antisense therapy, therapy by the method of RNA interference, gene therapy and the like. Each combination will be tailored to the type of tumor, stage, condition of the patient and previous therapy, as well as other factors considered by the treating physician.

[0154] , , (CDR-) ; . IgG , , . . IgG IgG . , hLL1 hLL2, -, , . , , .[0154] In a preferred embodiment, the antibodies that are used to treat human diseases are human or humanized (CDR-grafted) versions of antibodies; although murine and chimeric versions of antibodies can be used. IgG molecules of the same species as the delivery agents are generally preferred to minimize the immune response. This is especially important when considering retreatment. In humans, a human or humanized IgG antibody is less likely to elicit an anti-IgG immune response in patients. Antibodies such as hLL1 and hLL2 are rapidly internalized after binding to the internalizing antigen on the target cells, which means that the chemotherapeutic drug being transferred is also rapidly internalized in the cells. However, antibodies that have slower rates of internalization can also be used to provide selective therapy.

[0156] , , , . , NOTA (1,4,7--1,4,7- ), DOTA (1,4,7,10--1,4,7,10- ) TETA (), , , , . , . , 223Ra.[0156] Radionuclides and other metals can be delivered, for example, using chelating groups attached to the antibody or conjugate. Such metal chelate complexes can be made very stable by selecting the ring size for the metal of interest. Other ring-type chelates can be used such as macrocyclic polyethers to form complexes with 223 Ra.

Composition and introduction

[0167] , , , , , , , , , , , , , , , . . , , , , .[0167] Suitable routes of administration for the conjugates include, but are not limited to, oral, parenteral, subcutaneous, rectal, transmucosal, intestinal, intramuscular, intramedullary, intrathecal, direct intraventricular, intravenous, intravitreal, intraperitoneal, intranasal, or intraocular injection. The preferred routes of administration are parenteral. Alternatively, the compound can be administered locally rather than systemically, for example by injecting the compound directly into a solid tumor.

[0168] , . - . . ., , Ansel et al., PHARMACEUTICAL DOSAGE FORMS AND DRUG DELIVERY SYSTEMS, 5th Edition (Lea & Febiger 1990), Gennaro (ed.), REMINGTON'S PHARMACEUTICAL SCIENCES, 18th Edition (Mack Publishing Company 1990) .[0168] Immunoconjugates can be prepared according to known methods for preparing pharmaceutically acceptable compositions, wherein the immunoconjugate is combined in admixture with a pharmaceutically acceptable excipient. Sterile phosphate buffered saline is one example of a pharmaceutically acceptable excipient. Other suitable excipients are well known to those skilled in the art. See, for example, Ansel et al., PHARMACEUTICAL DOSAGE FORMS AND DRUG DELIVERY SYSTEMS, 5th Edition (Lea & Febiger 1990), and Gennaro (ed.), REMINGTON'S PHARMACEUTICAL SCIENCES, 18th Edition (Mack Publishing Company 1990) and their revised editions. ...
